post_text:
We still have 18 open slots for our 2020 Summer Freedom School program!

Follow this link to enroll your scholar: http://friendshipacademy.org/wp-content/uploads/pdfs/FreedomSchool/FreedomSchool-Application.pdf

To learn more about how COVID-19 has altered our program read our letter to families: https://docs.google.com/document/d/1ls_YaUo5G4ewKNPh7QX5xDBDzJEzYblcqCTX2TsB0i0/edit?usp=sharing

To learn more about our safety plan during Freedom School: https://drive.google.com/file/d/1fg1gG_7_y162uhMcyyON8NZj8_XgA0E5/view?usp=sharing

While the pandemic has altered the ways in which we conduct our program, we are still committed to providing all scholars with a valuable summer learning experience. We hope that with the support of families, we will have a fun and healthy summer together, the Freedom School way!

We still have 18 open slots for our 2020 Summer Freedom School program!

Follow this link to enroll your scholar: http://friendshipacademy.org/wp-content/uploads/pdfs/FreedomSchool/FreedomSchool-Application.pdf

To learn more about how COVID-19 has altered our program read our letter to families: https://docs.google.com/document/d/1ls_YaUo5G4ewKNPh7QX5xDBDzJEzYblcqCTX2TsB0i0/edit?usp=sharing

To learn more about our safety plan during Freedom School: https://drive.google.com/file/d/1fg1gG_7_y162uhMcyyON8NZj8_XgA0E5/view?usp=sharing

While the pandemic has altered the ways in which we conduct our program, we are still committed to providing all scholars with a valuable summer learning experience. We hope that with the support of families, we will have a fun and healthy summer together, the Freedom School way!

post_text: Our annual Wax Museum is one of our most popular Family Nights. Held at the end of Black History Month, this event is open to the community and allows scholars to honor their community by performing as ‘wax figures’ representing important people from African-American history. Every scholar has a part and has the opportunity to learn about someone whose story is connected to theirs. #FAAFCC

post_text: Leader in Me is our social-emotional learning program. Through Leader in Me, scholars use the “Seven Habits” to conduct themselves with integrity and contribute to the world around them. #TheFriendshipWay #FAALeadership

post_text: For our middle school scholars, Junior Achievement Biztown has become an integral part of their leadership curriculum. With this program, scholars are able to learn how to navigate the real world with workshops on how to start and run a business, manage a debit card and checking account and work as a team. Following these workshops, scholars then put what they learned to the test at the JA Biztown simulated city. #FAALeadership

post_text: Friendship Academy is an antidote to the opportunity gap experienced by so many African-American scholars in Minneapolis. In 2016, we were named a National Blue Ribbon School by the Department of Education, and have been a Minnesota “Beating the Odds” school for the past five years, as well as a “changing-the-odds” school for the past 3 years. #FAAAcademics

post_text:
Our rigorous curriculum gives scholars a background in essential knowledge. In Wit and Wisdom, our ELA curriculum, scholars read and re-read core texts, giving them the chance to experience the material on multiple levels. All scholars, regardless of starting ability, make predictions and engage in learning.

Our math curriculum, Eureka Math, places a major focus on ‘number sense,’ a modern way of thinking about math. With this approach, teachers can support all scholars and build success on achievement tests. #FAAAcademics

post_text:
Minnesota is now offering funds for families of children ages 5 to 18 who qualify for free or reduced-price school meals. The new program, called Pandemic EBT (P-EBT), will provide up to $325 per child that families can use to purchase nutritious food for their household. Approximately 350,000 Minnesota children could benefit.
Learn more at: www.mn.p-ebt.org

shared_text:
Spark-Y
June 5 at 10:56 PM ·

On behalf of the AACRT African American Community Response Team we will be giving 750 free Virtual Victory Gardens to individuals, families, and organizations in Minneapolis to inspire a movement of growing healthy food on our decks, homes, and community spaces.

Dr. B. Charvez Russell, Executive Director of Friendship Academy of the Arts, will lead a prayer and dedication at approximately 10:45 a.m. to help bless our victory gardens with the purpose of healing and uniting the community around justice. This will be live-streamed, please join us to take part in the healing and blessing.

At the request from the community, a Victory Garden site will be dedicated to George Floyd.

We want to thank all of you for your support, and to the many organizations and individuals mobilizing to make this movement possible: Green Garden Bakery, Appetite For Change, Grow North MN, Project Sweetie Pie, Ojibwa Healing, Positive Image Minneapolis, Olu's Beginnings, Summit Academy OIC, and more.

shared_text:
Vannessa Methona is with Tak Ting Noy Noy.
May 4 at 4:23 PM ·

Heart full of gratitude ❤️ Reflecting on these past weeks I’m so happy my mom is coming around and recovering after being tested positive for COVID-19. Her strength and positivity is inspiring. Thank you for all the good thoughts and prayers from everyone 🙏🏽

Also, so happy to share that I renewed my contract as a 2nd grade teacher with Friendship Academy of the Arts 😍✨ So much to be thankful for. I wanted to do a quick humble brag too 😆, shout out to all the amazing educators who have gone above and beyond to make their scholars still feel their love from afar- and giving them a great education! You are so appreciated. Genuinely thankful is an understatement, y’all are a big deal that’s forsure ❤️❤️❤️ Happy Teacher Appreciation Week!

Nominations are now being accepted for school board members.
Nomination period: Monday, April 20, 2020 – Wednesday, May 13, 2020. Nominations close at 3:00 p.m. on Wednesday, May 13th, 2020.

Persons eligible to serve on the board: FAA parents, FAA teachers, and community members who do not have children enrolled in the school.
7 board members are to be elected for 1 or 2 year terms:July 1, 2020 – June 30, 2021 or July 1, 2020 – June 30, 2022.

The composition of the board will be:
1 or more FAA Parents, 1 or more FAA Teachers, and up to 5 community members.

Interested persons should complete the nomination form and return to the school via:
by clicking on this link https://form.jotform.com/201168972000043.

Join us. We look forward to collaborating with our community.

post_text:
We love you, Mr. B! Thank you for always supporting our scholars' development as artists.

"My heart is full. I've been struggling as an Educator with Distance Learning. But NOT today. I was able to have a wonderful Zoom Meeting with The Billingsley School of Music & Arts students of Friendship Academy of the Arts. One student wrote two songs already and we're planning an all school Virtual Music Performance. I LOVE education Man. It's so important. Take nothing for granted is what we learned today."
shared_text:
David Billingsley III is feeling refreshed.
May 1 at 5:45 PM ·

My heart ❤️ is full.

I've been struggling as an Educator with Distance Learning. But NOT today. I was able to have a wonderful Zoom Meeting with The Billingsley School of Music & Arts students of Friendship Academy of the Arts.

One student wrote two songs already and we're planning an all school Virtual Music Performance. I LOVE education Man. It's so important.

Take nothing for granted is what we learned today. The things you say you don’t like and are tired of might be the exact thing you end up loving and missing more than ever.

#AccessStillChangesLives #BSOMA #FriendshipAcademy #OneStudentAtATime #NeverSayDie

post_text:
Parents/guardians: check your email!

As a guardian, you can now receive email summaries showing your student’s progress in their Google classroom! This is a great way to keep track of your child’s progress throughout distance learning and support their academic progress.

Guardian email summaries include:

Missing work—Work that’s late at the time the email was sent

Upcoming work—Work that’s due today and tomorrow (for daily emails) or work that’s due in the upcoming week (for weekly emails)

Class activity—Announcements, assignments, and questions recently posted by teachers

You can choose the frequency of the emails, such as daily or weekly, and unsubscribe at any time.

shared_text:
Pillsbury United Communities
April 9 at 7:09 PM ·

Essential Worker? Pillsbury Early Education Center (PEEC) located at Pillsbury House Theatre continues to have immediate openings for children of essential workers ages 16 months to 5 years.

PEEC is led by licensed, caring staff with decades of experience, and features an arts-integrated approach, as well as Spanish and ASL curriculum. Our center is NAEYC-accredited and 4-Star Parent Aware Rated.

Openings include daily, weekly, monthly and permanent placements. For more information or to set up a tour, contact PEEC Director Tammy Lyon at 612-787-3648.

post_text:
Over the course of this last week, the situation across our country -- and in our own community --has changed significantly with regard to the spread of COVID-19. We know that many of you are concerned about returning to school on Monday, and news about closures of large events and colleges and universities is raising questions about how schools in Minnesota should best respond.
We are in constant communication with the Minnesota Department of Health and the Minnesota Department of Education in our planning. We were informed this morning that additional guidance to schools is forthcoming from the state. Guidance from public health officials is crucial information to help us to make the best decisions for our community.
Please know that the safety and wellbeing of our entire community -- our students, teachers, staff, families and neighbors -- is our utmost concern. Visit our website at http://friendshipacademy.org/wp-content/uploads/pdfs/Coronavirus/Corona-Virus-Crisis-Mgmt-Plan.pdf to view our action plan.
text:
Over the course of this last week, the situation across our country -- and in our own community --has changed significantly with regard to the spread of COVID-19. We know that many of you are concerned about returning to school on Monday, and news about closures of large events and colleges and universities is raising questions about how schools in Minnesota should best respond.
We are in constant communication with the Minnesota Department of Health and the Minnesota Department of Education in our planning. We were informed this morning that additional guidance to schools is forthcoming from the state. Guidance from public health officials is crucial information to help us to make the best decisions for our community.
Please know that the safety and wellbeing of our entire community -- our students, teachers, staff, families and neighbors -- is our utmost concern. Visit our website at http://friendshipacademy.org/wp-content/uploads/pdfs/Coronavirus/Corona-Virus-Crisis-Mgmt-Plan.pdf to view our action plan.

We are aware of some colleges' and universities' recent decision to cancel classes and move to online learning. By the end of the week, we will have updated information on our website and social media pages regarding FAA's response to the COVID-19 pandemic. In the meantime, we wanted to share with you updated guidance regarding district-sponsored travel and information on personal travel in the wake of growing COVID-19 concerns.

FAA is following U.S. Department of State Travel Advisory guidelines. When guidelines reach Level 3, which advises no “non-essential travel,” FAA will cancel student and staff travel.

As always, our top priority is the safety of our students, staff and community. FAA continues to be in close contact with the Minnesota Department of Health (MDH) and public health agencies regarding the outbreak of COVID-19 and how we respond in our school district. Please see below to the Minnesota Department of Health to stay up to date on current conditions.

https://www.health.state.mn.us/#coronavirus

post_text:
A free arts opportunity!

"Mapping Black Identities" is a FREE exhibit at the Minneapolis Institute of Art.

https://new.artsmia.org/exhibition/mapping-black-identities/

"Championing the diverse experiences of artists from America, Africa, and the diaspora, this exhibition seeks to amplify underrepresented voices and create connections around the concept of Blackness in contemporary art across time and place. Mapping is a colonial practice tied to painful histories of conquest and domination. Here, mapping functions as a powerful way to reclaim spaces—such as the museum—that have traditionally excluded or overlooked work by Black artists."

Today concludes our #LoveTeaching campaign. Thank you to our community for following along!

“I always enjoyed school and the love of learning. I corralled the neighborhood kids into playing school and being my pupils. That was probably the beginning of my teaching that has led me to becoming an Urban Teaching graduate. I am now 10 years in the mix and am loving being at Friendship Academy of the Arts. The families, staff and STAR scholars make my cup overfloweth."

- Ms. Tiffini, middle school science and social studies teacher #JourneytoExcellence

Mrs. Kocina is the Curriculum and Assessment Coordinator at Friendship Academy. She was a fourth and fifth grade teacher at Friendship Academy for four years prior to assuming this role. She is pictured here with one of her scholars, Lanaya.

"I love teaching because not only can I make a difference in the lives of my students, but they also make a difference in my life without even realizing it! We learn from each other every day, whether it's a math lesson, life lesson, or just connecting over something new!" #LoveTeaching
